  "prompt": "How can you determine the ionic charge of sodium?",
  "response": "To determine the ionic charge of sodium, we can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Identify the Atomic Number**: Sodium (Na) has an atomic number of 11, meaning it has 11 protons in its nucleus.\n\n2. **Count Electrons**: In its neutral state, a sodium atom will have 11 electrons, balancing the positive charge of the protons.\n\n3. **Determine Electron Configuration**: The electron configuration of sodium is \\(1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^1\\). This shows that sodium has one electron in its outermost shell (the 3s subshell).\n\n4. **Consider Stability**: Atoms tend to achieve a stable electron configuration, often resembling the nearest noble gas. For sodium, losing one electron (the one in the 3s orbital) allows it to achieve the electron configuration of neon (\\(1s^2 2s^2 2p^6\\)), which is fully filled and stable.\n\n5. **Formation of Ion**: When sodium loses one electron to achieve stability, it becomes a positively charged ion known as a cation. \n\n6. **Determine Charge**: Since losing one electron results in a charge of +1 (the positive charge comes from having more protons than electrons), the ionic charge of sodium is \\(+1\\).\n\nTherefore, sodium typically forms a cation with a charge of \\(+1\\) when it ionizes, represented as \\(Na^+\\).",
